01Gn 10:1 These are the records of Noah's sons, Shem, Ham and Japheth, to whom descendants were born after the flood. 
01Gn 10:2 Japheth's descendants included Gomer, Magog, Madai, Javan, Tubal, Meshech, and Tiras.
01Gn 10:3 Gomer's descendants included Ashkenaz, Riphath, and Togarmah.
01Gn 10:4 Javan's descendants included Elisha, Tarshish, Kittim, and Dodanim, 
01Gn 10:5 from whom the coastal peoples spread into their own lands and nations, each with their own language and family groups.
01Gn 10:6 Ham's descendants included Cush, Egypt, Put, and Canaan.
01Gn 10:7 Cush's descendants included Seba, Havilah, Sabtah, Raamah, and Sabteca. Raamah's descendants included Sheba and Dedan.
01Gn 10:8 Cush fathered Nimrod, who became the first fearless leader throughout the land. 
01Gn 10:9 He became a fearless hunter before the Lord. That is why it is said, "Like Nimrod, a fearless hunter before the Lord." 
01Gn 10:10 His kingdom began in the region of Shinar with the cities of Babylon, Erech, Akkad, and Calneh. 
01Gn 10:11 From there he went north to Assyria and built Nineveh, Rehoboth-ir, Calah, 
01Gn 10:12 along with Resen, which was located between Nineveh and the great city of Calah.
01Gn 10:13 Egypt fathered the Ludites, the Anamites, the Lehabites, the Naphtuhites,
01Gn 10:14 the Pathrusites, the Casluhites (from which came the Philistines), and the Caphtorites.
01Gn 10:15 Canaan fathered Sidon his firstborn, along with the Hittites, 
01Gn 10:16 the Jebusites, the Amorites, the Girgashites, 
01Gn 10:17 the Hivites, the Arkites, the Sinites, 
01Gn 10:18 the Arvadites, the Zemarites, and the Hamathites. Later, the Canaanite families were widely scattered. 
01Gn 10:19 The Canaanite border extended south from Sidon toward Gerar as far as Gaza, and east toward Sodom, Gomorrah, Adinah, and Zeboiim, as far as Lasha.
01Gn 10:20 These are Ham's descendants, listed by their families, each with their own lands, language, and family groups.
01Gn 10:21 Shem, Japheth's older brother, also had descendents. Shem was the father of the descendents of Eber. 
01Gn 10:22 Shem's sons included Elam, Asshur, Arpachshad, Lud, and Aram.
01Gn 10:23 Aram's descendants included Uz, Hul, Gether, and Mash.
01Gn 10:24 Arpachshad fathered Cainan, Cainan fathered Shelah, and Shelah fathered Eber. 
01Gn 10:25 To Eber were born two sons. One was named Peleg, because the earth was divided during his lifetime. His brother was named Joktan.
01Gn 10:26 Joktan fathered Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah, 
01Gn 10:27 Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah, 
01Gn 10:28 Obal, Abimael, Sheba, 
01Gn 10:29 Ophir, Havilah, and Jobab. All these were Joktan's descendants. 
01Gn 10:30 Their settlements extended from Mesha towards Sephar, the eastern hill country. 
01Gn 10:31 These are Shem's descendants, listed by their families, each with their own lands, language, and family groups. 
01Gn 10:32 These are the families of Noah's sons, according to their records, in their nations. From these, the nations on the earth spread out after the flood.
01Gn 11:1 There was a time when the entire earth spoke a common language with an identical vocabulary. 
01Gn 11:2 As people migrated westward, they came across a plain in the region of Shinar and settled there. 
01Gn 11:3 They said to each other, "Come on! Let's burn bricks thoroughly." They used bricks for stone and tar for mortar. 
01Gn 11:4 Then they said, "Come on! Let's build ourselves a city and a tower, with its summit in the heavens, and let's make a name for ourselves so we won't be scattered over the surface of the whole earth."
01Gn 11:5 However, the Lord descended to look over the city and the tower that the humans were building. 
01Gn 11:6 The Lord said, "Look! They are one people with the same language for all of them, and this is only the beginning of what they will do. Nothing that they have a mind to do will be impossible for them! 
01Gn 11:7 Come on! Let's go down there and confuse their language, so that they will not understand each other's speech."6
01Gn 11:8 So the Lord scattered them abroad from there over the surface of the whole earth, so that they had to stop building the city. 
01Gn 11:9 Therefore it was called Babylon, because there the Lord confused the language of all the earth, and from there the Lord scattered them over the surface of the entire earth.
01Gn 11:10 These are the family records of Shem. When Shem had lived 100 years, he fathered Arpachshad two years after the flood. 
01Gn 11:11 Shem lived 500 years after he fathered Arpachshad and had other sons and daughters. 
01Gn 11:12 When Arpachshad had lived 35 years, he fathered Cainan. 
01Gn 11:13 After he fathered Cainan, Arpachshad lived 430 years and had other sons and daughters, and then died. Cainan lived 130 years and fathered Shelah. After he fathered Shelah, Cainan lived 330 years and had other sons and daughters, and then died.
01Gn 11:14 When Shelah had lived 30 years, he fathered Eber. 
01Gn 11:15 After he fathered Eber, Shelah lived 403 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:16 When Eber had lived 34 years, he fathered Peleg. 
01Gn 11:17 After he fathered Peleg, Eber lived 430 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:18 When Peleg had lived 30 years, he fathered Reu. 
01Gn 11:19 After he fathered Reu, Peleg lived 209 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:20 When Reu had lived 32 years, he fathered Serug. 
01Gn 11:21 After he fathered Serug, Reu lived 207 years and had other sons and daughters. 
01Gn 11:22 When Serug had lived 30 years, he fathered Nahor. 
01Gn 11:23 After he fathered Nahor, Serug lived 200 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:24 When Nahor had lived 29 years, he fathered Terah. 
01Gn 11:25 After he fathered Terah, Nahor lived 119 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:26 When Terah had lived 70 years, he fathered Abram, Nahor, and Haran.
01Gn 11:27 Now these are the family records of Terah£º Terah fathered Abram, Nahor, and Haran; and Haran fathered Lot. 
01Gn 11:28 Haran died during his father's lifetime in the land of his birth, that is, in Ur of the Chaldeans.
01Gn 11:29 Abram and Nahor took wives for themselves. The name of Abram's wife was Sarai, and the name of Nahor's wife was Milcah. She was the daughter of Haran, who was the father of Milcah and Iscah. 
01Gn 11:30 Sarah was barren; she had not yet borne children.
01Gn 11:31 Terah took his son Abram, his grandson Lot (Haran's son), and his daughter-in-law Sarai, his son Abram's wife, and they journeyed together from Ur of the Chaldeans to go to the land of Canaan. But when they came as far as Haran, they settled there. 
01Gn 11:32 Terah lived for 205 years, and then died in Haran.
01Gn 12:1 The Lord spoke to Abram, "You are to leave your land, your relatives, and your father's house and go to the land that I'll show you. 
01Gn 12:2 I'll develop you into a great nation, I'll bless you, and I'll make your reputation great, so that you will be a blessing. 
01Gn 12:3 I'll bless those who bless you, but I'll curse the one who curses you, and through you all the people of the earth will be blessed."
01Gn 12:4 So Abram went out, as the Lord had spoken to him, and Lot accompanied him. Abram was 75 years old when he left Haran. 
01Gn 12:5 Abram took his wife Sarai, his nephew Lot, all the possessions they had accumulated, and the servants he had acquired while living in Haran. Then they set out to go to the land of Canaan. When they arrived in the land of Canaan, 
01Gn 12:6 Abram traveled through the land to the place called Shechem, as far as the oak of Moreh. At that time the Canaanites were in the land.
01Gn 12:7 Then the Lord appeared to Abram and said, "I'll give this land to your descendants." So Abram built an altar to the Lord, who had appeared to him. 
01Gn 12:8 From there Abram traveled on to the hill country east of Bethel and set up his tent, with Bethel on the west and Ai on the east. There he built an altar to the Lord and called on the name of the Lord. 
01Gn 12:9 Then Abram traveled on, continuing on into the Negev.
01Gn 12:10 There was a famine in the land, so Abram went down to Egypt to live because the famine was so severe. 
01Gn 12:11 When he was about to enter Egypt, he said to his wife Sarai, "Look, I'm aware that you're a beautiful woman. 
01Gn 12:12 When the Egyptians see you, they will say, 'She is his wife.' Then they'll kill me, but allow you to live. 
01Gn 12:13 Please say that you are my sister, so things will go well for me for your sake. That way, you'll be saving my life."1211
01Gn 12:14 As Abram was entering Egypt, the Egyptians noticed how beautiful Sarai was. 
01Gn 12:15 When Pharaoh's officials saw her, they brought her to the attention of Pharaoh and took the woman to Pharaoh's palace. 
01Gn 12:16 He treated Abram well because of her, so he acquired sheep, oxen, male and female donkeys, male and female servants, and camels. 
01Gn 12:17 But the Lord afflicted Pharaoh and his household with severe plagues because of Sarai, Abram's wife. 
01Gn 12:18 Pharaoh summoned Abram and asked, "What have you done to me! Why didn't you tell me that she was your wife -  
01Gn 12:19 Why did you say, 'She is my sister,' so that I took her as a wife for myself -  Now, here is your wife! Take her and get out!"1216
01Gn 12:20 So Pharaoh assigned men to Abram, and they escorted him, his wife, and all that he had out of the country.
01Gn 13:1 Abram traveled from Egypt, along with his wife and everyone who pertained to him, including Lot, to the Negev.
01Gn 13:2 Now Abram had become quite wealthy in livestock, silver, and gold. 
01Gn 13:3 He journeyed by stages from the Negev to Bethel, the place where his tent had formerly been, between Bethel and Ai, 
01Gn 13:4 where he had first built an altar. There Abram called on the name of the Lord.
01Gn 13:5 Lot, who was traveling with Abram, also had flocks of sheep, other herds, and tents. 
01Gn 13:6 But the land could not support them living together, because they had so many possessions that they could not stay together. 
01Gn 13:7 There was strife between the herdsmen in charge of Abram's livestock and the herdsmen in charge of Lot's livestock. Also, at that time the Canaanites and the Perizzites were living in the land.
01Gn 13:8 So Abram said to Lot, "Please, let's not have strife between you and me, or between your herdsmen and my herdsmen, since we are relatives. 
01Gn 13:9 Isn't the whole land before you -  Let's separate£º If you go to the left, then I will go to the right; if you go to the right, then I will go to the left."
01Gn 13:10 Lot looked around and noticed that the whole Jordan plain as far as Zoar was well-watered like the garden of the Lord or like the land of Egypt. (This was before the Lord destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah.) 
01Gn 13:11 So Lot chose for himself all the Jordan plain. Then Lot traveled eastward, and they separated from each other.
01Gn 13:12 So Abram lived in the land of Canaan, while Lot settled in the cities of the plain, setting up his tent in the vicinity of Sodom. 
01Gn 13:13 Now the men of Sodom were very evil and sinful in defiance of the Lord.
01Gn 13:14 After Lot had separated from Abram, the Lord said to Abram, "Look out from where you're living - to the north, south, east, and west, 
01Gn 13:15 because I'm going to give you and your descendants all of the land that you see forever. 
01Gn 13:16 I'll make your descendants as numerous as the dust of the earth, so that if one could count the dust of the earth, then your descendants could be counted. 
01Gn 13:17 Get up! Walk throughout the length and breadth of the land, because I'm going to give it to you."
01Gn 13:18 So Abram moved his tent and settled beside the oaks of Mamre that are by Hebron, where he built an altar to the Lord.
01Gn 14:1 At the time when Amrafel was king of Shinar, Arioch was king of Ellasar, Chedorlaomer was king of Elam, and Tidal was king of the Goiim, 
01Gn 14:2 they engaged in war against King Bera of Sodom, King Birsha of Gomorrah, King Shinab of Admah, King Shemeber of Zeboiim, along with the king of Bela (which was also known as Zaor). 
01Gn 14:3 All of this latter group of kings allied together in the Valley of Siddim (that is, the Salt Sea). 
01Gn 14:4 They were subject to Chedorlaomer for twelve years, but they rebelled in the thirteenth year.
01Gn 14:5 In the fourteenth year, Chedorlaomer and the kings with him came and defeated the Rephaites in Ashteroth-karnaim, the Zuzites in Ham, the Emites in Shaveh-kiriathaim, 
01Gn 14:6 and the Horites in the hill country of Seir, near El-paran by the desert. 
01Gn 14:7 Next they turned back and came to En-mishpat (which was also known as Kadesh) and conquered all the territory of the Amalekites, along with the Amorites who lived in Hazazon-tamar.
01Gn 14:8 Then the kings of Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, Zeboiim, and Bela (which was also known as Zoar) prepared for battle in the Valley of Siddim 
01Gn 14:9 against King Chedorlaomer of Elam, King Tidal of Goiim, King Amraphel of Shinar, and King Arioch of Ellasar - four kings against five. 
01Gn 14:10 Now the Valley of Siddim was full of tar pits, so when the kings of Sodom and Gomorrah fled, some of their people fell into them, while the rest fled to the hill country. 
01Gn 14:11 The conquerors captured all the possessions of Sodom and Gomorrah, including their entire food supply, and then left. 
01Gn 14:12 They also took Abram's nephew Lot and his possessions, since he was living in Sodom.
01Gn 14:13 Someone escaped, arrived, and reported what had happened to Abram the Hebrew, who was living by the oaks of Mamre the Amorite, whose brothers Eshcol and Aner were allied with Abram. 
01Gn 14:14 When Abram heard that his nephew had been taken prisoner, he gathered together 318 of his trained men, who had been born in his household, and they went out in pursuit as far as Dan. 
01Gn 14:15 During the night Abram and his servants divided his forces, conquered them, and pursued them as far as Hobah, north of Damascus. 
01Gn 14:16 He recovered all the goods and brought back his nephew Lot, together with his possessions, the women, and the other people.1415
01Gn 14:17 After Abram's return from defeating Chedorlaomer and the kings who were with them, the king of Sodom went out to meet with him in the Shaveh Valley (that is, the King's Valley). 
01Gn 14:18 King Melchizedek of Salem brought out bread and wine, since he was priest of God Most High. 
01Gn 14:19 Melchizedek blessed Abram and said, "Abram is blessed by God Most High, Creator of heaven and earth,
01Gn 14:20 and blessed be God Most High, who has delivered your enemies into your control." Then Abram gave him a tenth of everything.
01Gn 14:21 The king of Sodom said to Abram, "Give me the people, and you take the possessions for yourself."
01Gn 14:22 But Abram answered the king of Sodom, "I have made an oath to the Lord God Most High, Creator of heaven and earth, 
01Gn 14:23 that I will not take a thread or a sandal strap or anything that belongs to you, so you won't be able to say, 'I have made Abram rich.' 
01Gn 14:24 I will take nothing except what my warriors have eaten. But as for the share of the men who were allied with me, including Aner, Eshcol and Mamre, let them take their share."
01Gn 15:1 Some time later a message came from the Lord to Abram in a vision£º "Don't be afraid, Abram. I am your shield; your reward will be very great."
01Gn 15:2 But Abram replied, "Lord God, what can you give me since I continue to be childless, and the heir of my household is Eliezer from Damascus -  
01Gn 15:3 Look!" Abram said, "You haven't given me any offspring, so a servant born in my house is going to be my heir."
01Gn 15:4 A message came from the Lord to him again£º "This one will not be your heir. Instead, the one who comes from your body will be your heir." 
01Gn 15:5 Then the Lord brought him outside. "Look up at the sky and count the stars - if you can!" he said. "Your descendants will be that numerous." 
01Gn 15:6 Abram believed the Lord, and it was credited to him as righteousness.
01Gn 15:7 The Lord spoke to him, "I am the Lord, who brought you from Ur of the Chaldeans, to give you this land as an inheritance."
01Gn 15:8 But he replied, "Lord God, how will I know that I will inherit it?" 
01Gn 15:9 The Lord responded, "Bring me a three year old cow, a three year old female goat, a three year old ram, a turtledove, and a young pigeon."
01Gn 15:10 So Abram brought him all these animals and cut each of them in half, down the middle, placing the pieces opposite each other, but he did not cut the birds in half. 
01Gn 15:11 When birds of prey swooped down on the carcasses, Abram drove them away. 
01Gn 15:12 As the sun began to set, a deep sleep came over Abram, and suddenly a frightening and terrifying darkness descended on him.
01Gn 15:13 Then the Lord said to Abram, "You can be certain about this£º Your descendants will be foreigners in a land that isn't theirs. They will be slaves there and will be oppressed for 400 years. 
01Gn 15:14 However, I will judge the nation that they serve, and later they will come out with many possessions. 
01Gn 15:15 Now as for you, you'll go to your ancestors in peace - you'll be buried at a good old age. 
01Gn 15:16 Your descendants will return here in the fourth generation, since the iniquity of the Amorites has not yet run its course."
01Gn 15:17 When the sun had fully set and it was dark, a smoking fire pot and a fiery torch passed between the animal pieces. 
01Gn 15:18 That very day the Lord made this covenant with Abram£º "I'm giving this land to your descendants, from the river of Egypt to the great Euphrates River -  
01Gn 15:19 including the land of the Kenites, the Kenizzites, the Kadmonites, 
01Gn 15:20 the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Rephaim,
01Gn 15:21 the Amorites, the Canaanites, the Girgashites, and the Jebusites."
01Gn 16:1 Now Abram's wife Sarai had not borne a child for him. She had an Egyptian servant girl whose name was Hagar. 
01Gn 16:2 So Sarai said to Abram, "You are well aware that the Lord has prevented me from giving birth to a child. Go in to my servant, so that I may possibly bear a son through her." Abram listened to Sarai's suggestion, 
01Gn 16:3 so Abram's wife Sarai took her Egyptian servant, Hagar, and gave her as a wife to her husband Abram. This took place ten years after Abram had settled in the land of Canaan. 
01Gn 16:4 He went in to Hagar, and she became pregnant. When she realized that she was pregnant, she looked with contempt on her mistress.163
01Gn 16:5 Then Sarai told Abram, "My suffering is your fault! I gave my servant into your embrace, and when she discovered that she was pregnant, she looked on me with contempt. May the Lord judge between you and me!"
01Gn 16:6 Abram answered Sarai, "Look, your servant is under your control, so do to her as you wish." So Sarai dealt so harshly with Hagar that she ran away from Sarai.16
01Gn 16:7 The angel of the Lord found her by a spring of water in the desert on the road to Shur. 
01Gn 16:8 "Hagar, servant of Sarai," he asked, "Where are you coming from and where are you going?" She answered, "I am running away from my mistress Sarai."
01Gn 16:9 The angel of the Lord said to her, "You must go back to your mistress and submit to her authority." 
01Gn 16:10 The angel of the Lord also said to her, "I will greatly multiply your offspring, who will be too many to count.
01Gn 16:11 "Look, you are pregnant and will give birth to a son," the angel of the Lord continued to say to her. "You will name him Ishmael, because the Lord has heard your cry of misery. 
01Gn 16:12 He'll be a wild donkey of a man. He'll be against everyone, and everyone will be against him. He will live in conflict with all of his relatives."
01Gn 16:13 So she called the name of Lord who spoke to her, "You are 'God who sees,' because I have truly seen the one who looks after me."
01Gn 16:14 That's is why the spring was called, "The Well of the Living One who looks after me." It was between Kadesh and Bered.
01Gn 16:15 Hagar eventually gave birth to Abram's son. Abram named his son whom Hagar bore Ishmael. 
01Gn 16:16 Abram was 86 years old when Hagar gave birth to Ishmael for Abram.
01Gn 17:1 When Abram was 99 years old, the Lord appeared to Abram and announced, "I am God Almighty. Live in my presence and be blameless. 
01Gn 17:2 I'll establish my covenant between me and you, and I'll greatly increase your numbers." 
01Gn 17:3 Then Abram fell to the ground as God continued speaking to him.
01Gn 17:4 "Look, I have made a covenant with you. You will be the father of many nations. 
01Gn 17:5 Your name is no longer to be Abram. Instead your name will be Abraham, since I'll make you the father of many nations. 
01Gn 17:6 I'm going to cause you to become very fruitful, and I'll bring nations from you. Kings will come from you. 
01Gn 17:7 I'm establishing my covenant between me and you, and with your descendants who come after you throughout their generations as an eternal covenant, to be your God and your descendants' God after you. 
01Gn 17:8 I'll give to you and to your descendants the land to which you have traveled - all the land of Canaan - as an eternal possession. I will be their God."
01Gn 17:9 God continued to speak to Abraham, "You and your descendants who follow you are to keep my covenant, that is, you and your descendants after you, throughout their generations. 
01Gn 17:10 Here is my covenant that you are to observe, between me and you and your descendants that follow£º Every male among you is to be circumcised. 
01Gn 17:11 "You are all to be circumcised in the flesh of your foreskin, and this is to be the sign of the covenant between me and you. 
01Gn 17:12 Throughout your generations, every male among you who is eight days old is to be circumcised, including the servant born in your house or the one purchased from a foreigner, who is not of your offspring. 
01Gn 17:13 The servant born in your house or the one purchased with money is to be circumcised. My covenant is to remain in your flesh as an eternal covenant. 
01Gn 17:14 Any uncircumcised male who does not have the foreskin of his flesh circumcised, that male will be eliminated from his people because he has broken my covenant."
01Gn 17:15 God said to Abraham, "As for Sarai your wife, you are not to call her Sarai any longer, because her name is to be Sarah. 
01Gn 17:16 I will bless her. Furthermore, I will give you a son from her. I will bless her, so that nations, kings, and people will come from her."
01Gn 17:17 Abraham fell to the ground, laughed, and said to himself, "Can a child be born to a 100 year old man -  Can a 90 year old Sarah give birth?" 
01Gn 17:18 So Abraham responded to God, "If only Ishmael would live in your presence!"
01Gn 17:19 But God replied, "No, but your wife Sarah will give birth to a son by you, and you will name him Isaac. I will confirm my covenant with him as an eternal covenant for his descendants after him. 
01Gn 17:20 And as for Ishmael, I have heard you. I will bless him, and he will be fruitful. I will multiply him greatly, and he will father 12 tribal leaders. I will make him into a great nation. 
01Gn 17:21 But I will confirm my covenant with Isaac, whom Sarah will give birth for you at this time next year." 
01Gn 17:22 With that, God finished talking to Abraham, and ascended from him.17
01Gn 17:23 Abraham took his son Ishmael and all the servants born in his house or purchased with his money - every male among the men of Abraham's household - and he circumcised the flesh of their foreskin that very day, just as God had spoken to him.17 
01Gn 17:24 Abraham was 99 years old when he was circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin. 
01Gn 17:25 His son Ishmael was 13 years old when he was circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin. 
01Gn 17:26 Both Abraham and his son Ishmael were circumcised on that very day. 
01Gn 17:27 Every man born in his household, as well as those who had been purchased with money from a foreigner, were circumcised with him.1726
01Gn 18:1 Later, the Lord appeared to Abraham by the oaks of Mamre, as Abraham was sitting near the entrance to his tent during the hottest part of the day. 
01Gn 18:2 He glanced up and saw three men standing there not far from him. As soon as he noticed them, Abraham ran from the tent entrance to greet them and bowed down to the ground. 
01Gn 18:3 "My lords," he said to them, "if I have found favor with you, please don't leave your servant. 
01Gn 18:4 Let a little water be brought to wash your feet, and then rest under the tree. 
01Gn 18:5 I'll bring some food for you, and after that you may continue your journey, since you have come by your servant's way." So they replied, "Do what you have said." 
01Gn 18:6 Abraham hurried into the tent to Sarah and said, "Quick! Three measures of the best flour! Knead it and make flat bread."
01Gn 18:7 Next, Abraham ran to the herd, found a choice and tender calf, and gave it to the young men, who went off in a hurry to prepare it. 
01Gn 18:8 Then he took curds, milk, and the calf that had been prepared, and placed it in front of them. Then he stood by them under the tree while they ate.
01Gn 18:9 They asked him, "Where is your wife Sarah?" "There, in the tent," he replied.
01Gn 18:10 Then one of them said, "I will certainly return to you in about a year's time. By then, your wife Sarah will have borne a son." Now Sarah was listening at the tent entrance behind him. 
01Gn 18:11 Abraham and Sarah were old, well advanced in age, and Sarah was beyond the age of childbearing. 
01Gn 18:12 That's why Sarah laughed to herself, thinking, "After I have grown old and my husband is old, am I going to have sex?"
01Gn 18:13 The Lord asked Abraham, "Why did Sarah laugh and think, 'Am I really going to bear a child, since I am so old?' 
01Gn 18:14 Is anything impossible for the Lord -  At the time set for it, I will return to you - about a year from now - and Sarah will have a son."
01Gn 18:15 But Sarah denied it. "I didn't laugh," she claimed, because she was afraid. He replied, "No! You did laugh!"
01Gn 18:16 After this, the men set out from there and looked out over Sodom. Abraham went with them to send them off.
01Gn 18:17 "Should I hide from Abraham what I am about to do," the Lord asked, 
01Gn 18:18 "since Abraham will become a great and powerful nation, and all the nations of the earth will find blessing through him -  
01Gn 18:19 Indeed, I have made myself known to him in order that he may charge his sons and his household after him to keep the way of the Lord, and to do what is right and just, so that the Lord may bring about for Abraham what he has promised."
01Gn 18:20 The Lord also said, "How great is the outcry against Sodom and Gomorrah! Their sin is so very serious! 
01Gn 18:21 I'm going down to see whether they have acted according to the outcry that has reached me. If not, I wish to know." 
01Gn 18:22 Then two of the men turned away from there and walked toward Sodom, while Abraham remained standing in the presence of the Lord.
01Gn 18:23 Abraham approached and asked, "Will you actually sweep away the righteous along with the wicked -  
01Gn 18:24 Perhaps there are 50 righteous ones within the city. Will you actually sweep it away and not forgive the place for the sake of the 50 righteous that are found there -  
01Gn 18:25 Far be it from you to do such a thing - to kill the righteous along with the wicked, so that the righteous and the wicked are treated alike! Will the Judge of all the earth not do what is right?"
01Gn 18:26 The Lord said, "If I find in Sodom 50 righteous people within the city, I will forgive the whole place for their sake."
01Gn 18:27 Abraham answered, "Look, even though I am only dust and ashes, I've ventured to speak to my Lord. 
01Gn 18:28 What if there are five less than 50 righteous ones -  Will you bring destruction upon the city because of the five?" He said, "I won't destroy it if I find 45 there."
01Gn 18:29 Abraham continued to speak to him, asking, "What if 40 are found there?" He replied, "I won't do it for the sake of the 40."
01Gn 18:30 Abraham then said, "I hope my Lord will not be angry if I speak. What if 30 are found there?" He answered, "I won't do it for the sake of the 30." 
